One year after the death of twenty people including primary school pupils in a three-storey building at Ita Faji, Lagos Island, human rights lawyer Mr. Femi Falana (SAN) has called for prosecution of building collapse offenders in the country to act as deterrence to others. Falana who stated this at a rally, organised by the Nigerian Institute Of Building (NIOB) to commemorate 2020 Builders’ Day in Lagos said his firm would offer free legal services to the institute in prosecuting building collapse offenders. He called on builders led by their President Kunle Awobodu to Ita Faji School located at No 63 Massey Street where the pupils were killed by the collapsed building on March 13 the 2019 to lay wreaths to be vigilant and ensure the arrest of quacks and corrupt contractors, compromising construction standards in the country. He said, “ Since the government has abdicated their responsibilities, the NIOB has to be vigilant and ensure that fake builders and quacks in the building industry are arrested and prosecuted by government. “Henceforth, we are going to work with this institute to ensure that those who are so callous to sacrifice the lives of people because they want to cut corners are dealt with.’’ Also speaking, the President of the NIOB, Mr. Kunle Awobodu, thanked Falana for his offer to collaborate with NIOB to end the menace of building collapse in the country. Awobodu said that professional builders must take their rightful places as managers of building production and construction processes in Nigeria. “Our nation needs not to continue to waste lives and properties while it has stock of specialists with the appropriate body of knowledge for the construction of lasting and sustainable buildings.” 